    "Usually, genomic information is extracted after a cancer has been diagnosed and followed up histologically.",
    "As a result, DL in clinical genomics is more involved in the advanced tasks, e.g., finding biomarkers for certain therapies or drug-response, rather than streamlining workflows by diagnosing cancer.",
    "Nevertheless, DL can be utilized in patient cases where the diagnosis is not straightforward.",
    "For example, in 2020, Zaoh et al. [66] (Fig.",
    "2a) used a DL model to predict the original tumor tissue for patients with cancer of unknown primary from RNA-sequencing data."
